      "year": 2025,
      "abstract": "The article examines problems that arise when trying to explain social reality. It appears that a genuine explanation must be able to answer the following questions: how are peo\u00adple able to comprehend complex phenomena of the social world (such as institutions) that are not related to the reality of physical bodies; how can each individual possess knowl\u00adedge of a potentially unlimited set of social situations, involving a potentially unlimited number of rules for building social relations; and how is the universality of institutions combined with their cultural and situational variability. Similar questions have been raised in linguistics within the framework of universal grammar and some internalist ap\u00adproaches to language and thought. Within the sociological tradition, externalist interpreta\u00adtions of the nature of social reality and the phenomenon of social order have historically prevailed. However, the arguments previously proposed in favor of an innate language faculty also seem legitimate in relation to the human ability to process and represent so\u00adcial information \u2013 namely, institutional thinking. Intuitive knowledge of the system of so\u00adcial world rules (knowledge of society) requires solving the \u201cPlato\u2019s problem\u201d: con\u00adstructing models of perception and learning (processing and representation of social information). From the author\u2019s point of view, the assumption of \u201cmental tools\u201d could ex\u00adplain how all participants in interaction grasp the common logic of constructing institu\u00adtional forms.",
